- The Visitor Pattern is a Behavioral Design Pattern that allows adding new operations to existing 
classes without modifying those classes.
- The Visitor Pattern is used when we want to perform different operations on a group of objects 
without changing their classes. The operation is placed inside a separate Visitor class.

- Normally, if we want to add a new functionality to a class, we modify the class and add a new method. 
As the application grows, this causes classes to become larger and harder to maintain.

- The Visitor Pattern solves this problem by moving the new functionality into a separate Visitor class. 
The original classes remain unchanged, while different visitors can perform different operations on the 
same objects. This follows the Open/Closed Principle, because new operations can be added without 
modifying existing classes.


[Why do we need Visitor Pattern?]

Suppose we have
    Circle
    Rectangle
    Triangle

Today each class contains: draw()

Tomorrow the client asks for calculateArea()

Next month, calculatePerimeter()

Then exportToPDF()

Without Visitor, we have to modify every shape class every time.

eg. In gaming applicaitons visitor pattern is used, as class methods goes increasing as time grows.

#[How it is differnet from Strategy Pattern]
- In Strategy pattern, single clas has fix number of operations or methods but every method could have
different ways(Strategy) to do it.

- Whereas, In Visitor Design pattern, number of operations or methods keeps adding or changes as time grows.